        <div class="col-md-6">
          <p>
To have access to “free” prenatal care, it is  required to register with the National Health Service (SSN) first to have a residence permit (as Employees, Self-employed, Enrolled in the unemployment listings, Family reunion, Asylum). For further info contact: UNHCR italy: Adress: Via Alberto Caroncini, 19, Roma RM, Italy Telefon:+39 06 802121
</p>
 <p> A fee is required and must be paid at a local post office before visiting the ASL office (if you need it). 
<p>
In Italy pregnant women may be entitled to the following examinations free of charge:
<ul>
  <li> Blood tests (including tests for toxoplasmosis)</li>
<li>Three echographies (ultrasound scans) during the course of the pregnancy </li>
<li>A tri-test done at approximately the fifteenth week to check the possibility of the baby having Down's Syndrome. </li>
<ul>
During delivery the mother is entitled to have the father (or any other person of her choice) with her.
</p>
<p>
There are English speaking centers,  for example: <br>
The Birth Center, <br>
At: Via Marmorata 169, sc. 3 int. 1, 00153 Rome<br>
Tel: +39 06 5758648 / +39 06 57300707<br>
Certain centers may offer assistance without asking any types of documents: <br>
e.g.  Poliambulatorio di Emergency a Palermo <br>
(Monday-Friday h. 9,00 / 18,00)<br>
(all types of prenatal cares except delivery)<br>
Via G. La Loggia 5/a<br>
90129 Palermo<br>
Tel: +39 091 6529498
</p>
